1. We have, $$\Delta  = \left| {\matrix{
   {{{\cos }^2}{\alpha  \over 2}} &amp; {{{\sin }^2}{\alpha  \over 2}}  \cr 
   {{{\sin }^2}{\beta  \over 2}} &amp; {{{\cos }^2}{\beta  \over 2}}  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ = {\cos ^2}{\alpha  \over 2}{\cos ^2}{\beta  \over 2} - {\sin ^2}{\alpha  \over 2}{\sin ^2}{\beta  \over 2}$$<br><br>$$ = \left( {\cos {\alpha  \over 2}\cos {\beta  \over 2} + \sin {\alpha  \over 2}\sin {\beta  \over 2}} \right)\left( {\cos {\alpha  \over 2}\cos {\beta  \over 2} - \sin {\alpha  \over 2}\sin {\beta  \over 2}} \right)$$<br><br>$$ = \cos \left( {{{\alpha  - \beta } \over 2}} \right)\cos \left( {{{\alpha  + \beta } \over 2}} \right)$$<br><br>$$ = \cos \left( {{{\alpha  - \beta } \over 2}} \right)\cos 45^\circ $$ [$$\because$$ $$\alpha  + \beta  = 90^\circ $$]<br><br>$${1 \over {\sqrt 2 }}\cos \left( {{{\alpha  - \beta } \over 2}} \right)$$<br><br>2. The maximum value of $$\cos {{\alpha  - \beta } \over 2}$$ is 1.<br><br>$$\therefore$$ The maximum value of determinant is $${1 \over {\sqrt 2 }}$$.<br><br>Hence, both statements are correct.
